sols_latex:
We want to evaluate this integral:

\begin{align*}
\int (x + 1) \ln(x) \, dx
\end{align*}

We start by making the following substitution:

\begin{align*}
y = \ln(x).
\end{align*}

Then

\begin{align*}
dy \, = \frac{1}{x} \, dx
\end{align*}

and thus

\begin{align*}
dx = x \, dy
\end{align*}

So, after making the substitution, the integral becomes

\begin{align*}
\int (x+1) y x\, dy.
\end{align*}

But because

\begin{align*}
y = \ln(x),
\end{align*}

it follows that

\begin{align*}
x = e^y.
\end{align*}

So the integral reduces to

\begin{align*}
\int e^y (e^y + 1) y \, dy
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
= \int (e^{2y} + e^y) y \, dy
\end{align*}

Now, we apply integration by parts with

\begin{align*}
u = y
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
du = dy
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
dv = e^{2y} + e^y
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
v = \frac{1}{2} e^{2y} + e^y
\end{align*}

So,

\begin{align*}
\int u \, dv = u v - \int v \, du
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
= y(\frac{1}{2} e^{2y} + e^y) - \int \frac{1}{2} e^{2y} + e^y \, dy
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
= y(\frac{1}{2} e^{2y} + e^y) - \frac{1}{4} e^{2y} - e^y + C.
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
= y(\frac{1}{2} (e^y)^2 + e^y) - \frac{1}{4} (e^y)^2 - e^y + C
\end{align*}

Finally, we substitute y = ln(x) back in:

\begin{align*}
= \frac{1}{2} x^2 \ln(x) + x \ln x - \frac{1}{4} x^2 - x + C
\end{align*}

So the integral is given by

\begin{align*}
\int (x + 1) \ln (x) dx = \frac{1}{2} x^2 \ln(x) + x \ln x - \frac{1}{4} x^2 - x + C
\end{align*}

\emph{This is not required in a complete solution, but it is recommended
to check your answer by differentiating:}

\begin{align*}
&\frac{d}{dx}\left(\frac{1}{2} x^2 \ln(x) + x \ln(x) - \frac{1}{4}x^2 - x + C\right) \\
&\quad = x \ln(x) + \frac{1}{2} x + \ln(x) + 1 - \frac{1}{2} x - 1 \\
&\quad = x \ln(x) + \ln(x) \\
&\quad = (x + 1) \ln(x). 
\end{align*}
